article.headline: Connecticut nearly squanders 10-point lead
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen buried the Indiana Fever
again.

She made two driving layups in the final two minutes to lift the
Sun to a 65-61 win over the Fever on Sunday, Connecticut's second
come-from-behind win over the Fever in less than a week.

Whalen finished with 13 points and three assists for the Sun,
less than a week after making a layup with 8.4 seconds left in
regulation to force overtime in the Sun's 79-77 win over Indiana on
Tuesday night.

"We just had to stay together," Whalen said. "It just shows
that if we stick together, good things are going to happen."

The Fever trailed by 13 points in the first half but went on a
13-0 run late in the second to take the lead. Tamika Catchings
capped the run with a 3-pointer as the shot clock expired for a
61-58 lead with 2:35 to play.

But Whalen and the Sun responded with a 7-0 run. After
Catchings' 3-pointer, Wendy Palmer hit a free throw and a layup and
Whalen scored on two acrobatic drives to the hoop, the last coming
with 21.8 seconds left to seal the win.

"She's a great point guard," Catchings said. "She's able to
get to the hole and create for her teammates and in doing so, she
opens up things for herself."

Catchings led the Fever with 20 points and White added 12 points
and five assists.

The Sun took a 45-34 lead at halftime, but the Fever settled
down in the second half and chipped away at the lead. They
committed just four of their 17 turnovers in the second half, but
their rally late in the second half drained their energy.

"We just didn't take advantage of our opportunities to score,"
Catchings said. "When you're down 11, it's kind of hard to come
all the way back."

The Sun have won seven of their last eight games and all three
meetings over the Fever this season, meaning they own the
tiebreaker if the two teams are tied for a playoff spot.

"We definitely don't want it to come down to us and Connecticut
for the playoffs at the end of the season," White said.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 11 of her 12 points in the first
half for the Sun, but Whalen was the star.

For most of the game, she thoroughly outplayed her veteran
counterpart, Kelly Miller.

Whalen grew up in Hutchinson, Minn., watching Miller and her
twin sister, Coco play at Mayo High School in Rochester. She
relished the chance to play against one of the players she so
admired growing up.

"They were great athletes and great players and did great
things for women's basketball in the state," Whalen said. "It's
great to see her and play against her."

Miller finished with eight points and tied a career-high with
six assists. The elder Minnesotan spent much of the evening chasing
the rookie with the boundless energy and the quick first step.

"It's a tough thing to do -- be a point guard as a rookie and
lead the team and make plays down the stretch," Miller said.
"It's very impressive."
